Package com.phasmidsoftware.dsaipg.adt.threesum

Class ThreeSumBenchmark

java.lang.Object
com.phasmidsoftware.dsaipg.adt.threesum.ThreeSumBenchmark
public class ThreeSumBenchmark extends Object
The ThreeSumBenchmark class provides a framework for evaluating and comparing the performance of various implementations of the Three-Sum algorithm. It supports benchmarking for cubic, quadratic, and quadrithmic implementations and logs the runtime results for analysis.

Benchmarks are executed on randomly generated input arrays, with configurable parameters like the number of runs, input size, and value range. The results are normalized according to theoretical time complexities (e.g., n^3, n^2 log n, n^2) for better interpretability.

    • ThreeSumBenchmark

      public ThreeSumBenchmark(int runs, int n, int m)
      Constructs a ThreeSumBenchmark instance to facilitate the performance evaluation of different implementations of the Three-Sum algorithm.
      Parameters:
      runs - the number of benchmark runs to perform. Represents how many times the benchmark will be executed to ensure consistency.
      n - the size of the input array to the Three-Sum algorithm. Represents the number of integers in the generated array for testing.
      m - the range of integers in the input array, where each integer lies within the range of -m through m-1. Determines the distribution of values in the generated test arrays.

  • Method Details

    • runBenchmarks

      public void runBenchmarks()
      Executes a series of performance benchmarks to evaluate the runtime efficiency of various implementations of the Three-Sum algorithm. The benchmarks are executed for three approaches: cubic, quadratic, and quadrithmic, with results logged for analysis purposes.

      The method performs the following tasks: 1. Logs the problem size `n` being tested. 2. Benchmarks the "ThreeSumQuadratic" implementation using its corresponding algorithm and time logger. 3. Benchmarks the "ThreeSumQuadrithmic" implementation with its respective algorithm and time logger. 4. Benchmarks the "ThreeSumCubic" implementation, but skips execution if the problem size exceeds a predefined limit (e.g., for scalability reasons).

      Each benchmark internally utilizes a supplier to generate input arrays, and applies a predefined number of runs to obtain averaged runtime measures.

    • main

      public static void main(String[] args)
      The main method serves as the entry point to the application. It sequentially executes performance benchmarks for various configurations of the Three-Sum problem. Each configuration specifies the number of runs, the input size, and the range of randomly generated integers for the Three-Sum algorithm.

      The benchmarks are designed to evaluate and log the performance of different algorithmic implementations: cubic, quadratic, and quadrithmic.

      Parameters:
      args - command-line arguments (not used in this application).
